</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul></li><li id="tree_64715614" class="comment oneline"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64715614" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64715614" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64715614" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64715614" name="comment_link_64715614" href="//slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23425724&amp;cid=64715614" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64715614)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64715614" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64715614); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~smoot123">smoot123</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~smoot123">( 1027084 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64715614"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64715614"><p><div class="quote"><p>Electronic labels may enable pricing per customer however, and this must not be allowed to happen.</p></div><p>I'm curious why you say this. Yes, it might be irritating as a consumer but put your and my personal feeling aside for a moment. Why exactly must this not be allowed? Prices get adjusted per customer in all sorts of other contexts (mostly big ticket items like cars, home renovations, legal fees, and the like). What makes groceries different? What's your ethical, moral, or legal basis for saying this would be bad?</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64715614">

</div>
