		 	<span id="comment_score_64715840" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64715840); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~davecb">davecb</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~davecb">( 6526 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64715840"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64715840">If the price changes after the time of the "offer" and "acceptance' (price is read, then the customer puts the product in their cart) and before the time of payment, then the seller is committing the <i>definition</i> of fraud in Canadian law.

There's case law on it, if you're interested in suits: <a href="https://www.canlii.org/en/on/onca/doc/1991/1991canlii2734/1991canlii2734.html" title="canlii.org">https://www.canlii.org/en/on/o...</a> [canlii.org]</div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64715840">

