		<div id="comment_body_64715590"><p>Here in Saskatchewan, Canada, Wal-Mart is already using eInk electronic tags in some areas of the store. This means they don't have to print out reams of paper tags and have staff members walking the aisles to change them. And because of the way they are designed, the eInk tags get a long, slow refresh cycle over the period of a day, as they're all <i>battery operated</i> and using the 432MHz or 915MHz frequency band for short-length, low bandwidth signalling</p><p>With frequent updates for things like "surge pricing", i<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

