		<div id="comment_body_64715552"><p><div class="quote"><p>I counted one aisle at the store I worked at then did the math, and figured we had roughly 10,000 unique tags in our small store. We had 2 full time and 1 part time employees dedicated to keeping tags up to date.</p></div><p>Odd part about this issue, is the actual age of electronic labels.  I&rsquo;ve seen them in some stores for many many years now.</p><p>Two full time and one part time likely amounts to over $100K annually in fully loaded burden on an employer today, not including human error, or the massive cost of labels and printers themselves annually.  What&rsquo;s the ROI on that to convert?  Maybe 3-5 years?  What is the benefit in using those employees far more efficiently elsewhere in the business?</p><p>Electronic labels are an old solution for an even older problem that probably shouldn&rsquo;t still exist.  Probably one of the most pain-n-the-ass things to deal with as a grocer.</p></div>
